                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2011/04/21/noodlesticks/341e9be5-e002-438d-8280-fe17cb4a81c1/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/noodlesticks" title="User profile page">noodlesticks</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 7:55AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Often make them - two tips, one is that to avoid the pizza becoming soggy with its topping, brush the top of the pizza with olive oil before you add the topping (then the topping sits on a sort of impermeable layer). Second, all pizzas have a tomato sauce layer. To make this, simply whizz cut fresh tomatoes with garlic, oregano, salt and pepper - never use onion. My take on pizza <a href="http://bit.ly/psOslz" rel="nofollow">here</a>.</p>
						
					</div>
