			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12316776">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/09/02/cta_262190_18/19f9c569-a6ee-42e7-943c-c9a24ff34350/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/takeonefamily" title="User profile page">takeonefamily</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 8:21AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Great advice on pizza baking. We have tried loads of different ways over the years, but I love <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=1GQUnFHcFTQolI6Y_lXWyDBQEnnEt18XwkB8EMQuzlwA" rel="nofollow">Dan Lepard'</a>s recipe for perfect pizza dough, although we do cheat and roll the dough.  We have a big round metal tray that is perforated which seems to give us the best bases, provided it is heated as high as our oven will go. I use passata with gently fried sliced garlic for my sauce and then whatever is in the fridge, but not pineapple!<br>I would love to try some of the Italian flours to see what difference they make, but I haven't found a supply in our area.<br>Leftovers make great lunchbox fillers, and Dan's recipe will also sit in the fridge for a week or 2 so you can make fresh pizza anytime.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
