			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317003">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/ocozinheiro/dadfe88c-ec03-4a0a-b0a5-a91bbc9bcc2d/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/ocozinheiro" title="User profile page">ocozinheiro</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 8:48AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>@idunnosomename.  <br></p><blockquote><p>I don't care what newspaper recipes keep saying, making pizza bases at home is a pain in the arse, so a few failed attempts meant no pizza ever graced my oven.</p></blockquote><p>Making your own pizza is so easy and such fun. The dough takes 10 minutes to make and the kneading is so therapeutic and quite a sexy experience. I always make a double quantity as it freezes very successfully. after de-frosting just repeat the process of covering it with a clean cloth and leave it in a warm place. make your dough in the morning leave it to rise and make a simple quick topping when you are ready to eat.How difficult is that?</p><p>The other big issue about Home made pizza as Felicity quite rightly points out is the<br>temperature of our domestic ovens. I follow the Heston thinking on this one and pre-heat the base of a large loose bottomed metal quiche pan. When it is too hot to touch remove it from the oven carefully with a thick cloth to a wooden board and slide your pizza base onto it<br>Add your chosen topping and bake on the hottest setting.Here is<a href="http://casarosada-algarve.blogspot.com/2011/01/tudo-acaba-em-pizza.html" rel="nofollow"> my take on pizza</a> which I adapted from a River cafe pasta recipe.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
