			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317417">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/JohnnyVodka" title="User profile page">JohnnyVodka</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:25AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I love messing around with homemade pizza, though results can be mixed.  How you approach the topping is important.  I find the sparser, the better - the more stuff you load on to it (esp veg and mozarella), the less crispy the base will be.  I like to reduce a can of plum tomatoes with (lightly fried) garlic and oregano, until I can see no liquid running about in the saucepan, then lightly cover the base with that.  Maybe a light scattering of mushrooms, pepper, chillies or whatever, and of course mozarella.</p><p>I also like Jamie Oliver's idea of half-cooking and freezing some extra bases.  These can then be covered with topping &amp; cooked from frozen at a later date.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
