			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317525">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/mccp" title="User profile page">mccp</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:31AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Another worthwhile article - thanks.</p><p>I'm lucky enough to have a pizza oven in my kitchen - a small commercial one is not so expensive compared to the price of a good cooker.</p><p>I make a tomato topping that was copied from a pizzeria in the South of France that goes down very well with most people:</p><p>For four 10"-12" pizzas:</p><p>Two cans of good quality tinned tomatoes (not ready chopped)<br>Two tablespoons of sugar<br>Olive oil<br>Salt and pepper</p><p>Dump the tinned tomatoes into a wide bottomed pan and then take each whole tomato out, cut off any skin or nasty bits and chop finely before returning to the pan. The idea is to make sure that you will end up with no big lumps in the sauce.</p><p>Add a tablespoon of sugar for each tin of tomatoes that you use. This cuts the acidity down and enhances the tomato flavour. The recipe easily scales up, I've made it with 8 tins of toms before.</p><p>Generously add olive oil, I'd suggest that at least a tablespoon per tin of toms.</p><p>Salt and pepper to taste.</p><p>Now bring to a boil and then simmer, stirring occasionally for 20 to 30 mins to reduce to a saucy paste.</p><p>In our house we reckon that a margarita (tomato sauce and mozzarella) should be the best pizza if you have a good base, sauce and mozzarella. Some prefer a caperita which has capers and salted anchovies.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
