			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317545">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/09/02/cta_262190_08/878be48c-e80a-4420-bc84-0a1b0ca58370/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/mrwicksy" title="User profile page">mrwicksy</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:32AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I have homemade pizza every week, and have done for a couple of years now. Friday treat.</p><p>GIA Sundried Tomato Puree is good if you're lazy and can't be bothered to make tomato sauce properly. Watch what you put on top though as it can be a little salty.</p><p>I've also used HP Barbecue Sauce and even Levi Roots Reggae Reggae Sauce and they weren't too bad, if a little dry. I'm actually gonna try and make proper tomato sauce tomorrow night and see where it gets me (I've made it a lot before for pasta just never thought to use it on pizza)</p><p>Buffallo Mozzarella has a lovely taste, the only downside being that it can make it a bit soggy and "pond" on the top (oven heat, probably), so the "shrink-wrapped blocks" of Mozzarella are a little less messy.</p><p>I tend to use parma ham, a nice salami (from a proper sausage rather than the presliced, as i don't like the oilyness of those so much), pancetta, and maybe roast chicken from leftovers or those pre-cooked whole pieces. Also, some chilli, maybe shallots or spring onions too.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
