			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317674">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/HopefulJ" title="User profile page">HopefulJ</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:41AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I've tried making the dought with 00 flour, but couldn't see any appreciable difference - I use half strong white bread flour and half ordinary plain flour - only 1/2 a tsp of dried yeast for 500g flour, though, and a good glug of olive oil. I put the dough, when mixed, into the fridge and use it the next day - makes for a better taste and texture. </p><p>Toppings - any combination of tomato, garlic, oregano, red onion, pepperoni or chorizo (not authentic, I know, but still delish), gruyere (ditto - all the lovely stringiness of mozzarella, but with more bite), parma ham or pancetta. </p><p>Had a lovely potato and rosemary pizza in Florence once - with tiny bits of spicy sausage on it - have not tried it at home, though. </p><p>Pineapple on pizza - along with other travesties, like chicken tikka pizza - must be stopped at all costs.</p>
						
					</div>
