                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/alansokalwasright" title="User profile page">alansokalwasright</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:41AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>At the risk of sounding a snob (and it is admittedly particularly silly to be a snob about something like pizza, which is the ultimate <i>cucina povera</i>, but I am going to be a pizza snob anyway) American 'pizza' is sometimes decent, but really should not be called 'pizza' at all.  There is a reason when it was first invented it was called 'pizza pie': it bears more resemblance to the (obese) bastard child of foccaccia and poor-quality industrial 'cheeze' than anything like the real thing.</p><p>Neapolitan pizza, on the other hand, particularly a margherita with fresh balls of mozzarella (ideally not tinted blue from the camorra's toxic waste dumps) borders on the sublime.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
