			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317886">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/09/04/OldBristolian/bf65599a-bc7b-42c5-a4e7-285ee62df4a8/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/OldBristolian" title="User profile page">OldBristolian</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:53AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Making pizza dough at home is easy if you use a bread machine.  Take it out, roll it out and leave it to prove (sp?) a little.</p><p>Make your own pizza sauce - must confess the wife does this - but it involves tinned tomatoes/passata, garlic, onions, seasoning etc then blend it.  She makes loads and then freezes the excess in ice cube trays for future use (just pop out a couple of cubes and defrost).</p><p>As for the toppings - use quality ingredients; parma ham is much nicer than regular ham, good quality mozerella (without going over the top), decent italian salami.  Yeah, okay so that's a blokey pizza but you get the idea.</p><p>Importantly - put your toppings on and put the cheese on top as this stops your ham/salami from burning.</p><p>Oh and finally - how to cook?</p><p>If you have an AGA (I see those backs going up) then put it straight onto the base of the hot oven - this works like a bread oven and it unbeatable.</p><p>With conventional ovens use a pizza stone - get it really hot, take the stone out of the oven (they come with a stand) and then make the pizza on that hot stone (be bloody careful you don't burn yourself) and then return the stone with the pizza on it to the oven.  Works a treat and worth the hassle.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
