<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/alloba" title="User profile page">alloba</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:55AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I recently lived in Rome for four years.  There is no comparison between the Roman style pizza to those found in Napoli. The neapolitan pizza is streets ahead...<br>And I ate in Neapolitan (the proprietors originating from Napoli) pizzerie all over Italy. They just weren't the same.<br>The answer to my frequently posed question 'why are pizzas in Napoli, made by Neapolitans, so individual and special' was always 'the water used in the dough'.</p>
						
