			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317933">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/mk11/1ac52cb9-8527-4875-9477-38f6fd99825d/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/mk11" title="User profile page">mk11</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:56AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>My notes:</p><p>Recipes which are too precise, such as 320ml water, are pointless. You're going for texture and it depends on the combination of flour and water, also their type, and kneading. Fresh yeast is much better and keeps for about two weeks. It should be malleable, springy and not sticky. Just try and get a feel for it.</p><p>Worth making dough day before and letting it rest in fridge overnight. If not, let it rise in oven at lowest setting (less than 50C) until it doubles in volume (45-60m). Or make more, eat half and have focaccia for breakfast.</p><p>Prepare the base on parchment paper, much less messy and more forgiving if your dough isn't quite right. Dust with flour on top and spread out with palms from centre. Or roll.</p><p>Half an hour should get your oven hot enough. Use rung just beneath middle one.</p><p>Don't be anal about it. Food is supposed to be fun</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
