			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12317967">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/pdbright" title="User profile page">pdbright</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 9:59AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>A couple of things I think are important:<br>1. Whether you are using fresh or tinned tomatoes it is important to drain most of the liquid (and preferably the pips) from them (I usually do this by leaving them in a sieve over the sink for a while, with an occasional shake).<br>2. The buffalo mozzarella can be quite watery so it is sometimes helpful to soak up a bit of the excess fluid with kitchen towel.<br>3. A layer of olive oil is important before the addition of other ingredients.<br>4. Controversially I don't think it is essential to have the oven extremely hot - I have had excellent results in the top of the oven (on a thin tray) at gas mark 7 or 8 for around 15 minutes - crisp on the bottom with lightly raised edges and softer heat bubbles throughout.<br>5. Scatter any basil leaves immediately after it comes out of the oven (never put them on before cooking(!) - but perhaps I'm the only one who has made this ridiculous mistake.<br>6. Like the basil, really good quality olive oil should be drizzled on after it is cooked.<br>7. I also like them fairly simple (olive oil, a tomato sauce base with a touch of garlic, buffalo mozzarella and a bit of grated parmesan - plus v g olive oil and basil leaves after it is cooked).  Occasionally I have added some olives and/or anchovies - which can work very well.<br>8.  I always use '00' flour and therefore can't vouch for other types...</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
