			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12318016">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/amybeach/3446cfca-9efc-4eed-84b1-5e5634f1c6db/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/amybeach" title="User profile page">amybeach</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 10:02AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I make good pizza all the time now but there was definitely a learning curve. Many factors go into it, some of them oven-specific, and it takes a while, and some luck, to come up with the right formula. I've also concluded that it doesn't have to be round; my foot-shaped pizzas are now famous amongst my friends. </p><p>I have found that slow-fermenting in the fridge - 3 days is best - really adds flavour to the crust, but most of all it makes it relaxed, easy to handle, and stretchy: you can get it thin enough to see through without breaking. Type 00 flour is good or, as Felicity suggests, half 00 and half plan. I love Dan Lepard but I don't get on with his pizza dough recipe; it's too bready for me. </p><p>@applespider thanks so much for the granite worktop saver tip! I have finally sacked my John Lewis pizza stone, which has no heat capacity and, I swear, makes the crust even less crisp than doing it on a baking sheet.</p><p>Another hint I would offer is that making the pizza on baking paper makes it much easier to slide into the oven without affecting the crispness.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
