						</li>
					</ul>
				</li>
				
			</ul>
		
			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-12318059">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2011/03/15/Benulek/5eb266e6-22bb-49be-9bd5-a26322d2210a/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/Benulek" title="User profile page">Benulek</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">8 September 2011 10:05AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>I like the base to be as thin as possible, but this is a matter of personal preference rather than some tiresome pretence at 'authenticity'. It's peasant food - any claim to regional provenance or 'correctness' of recipe is ahistorical protectionist bunk.</p><p>Base made in breadmaker. There's no reason not to use technology while we have it. Some will sneer at the idea of not working the dough with your hands, but they're usually the sort of people who think it is less important that pizza has been made than that they be seen to have made it.</p><p>Tomato sauce made by thickening a passata with some garlic, a sprinkling of herbs, a bit of olive oil and some balsamic vinegar.</p><p>Toppings - mozzarella and whatever I have knocking about. Again, the whole 'authenticity' thing is usually wheeled out here. People will tell you that, say, chicken on pizza is a no-no. Well, one of my favourite pizzas uses leftover barbecued chicken, and by making use of leftovers I am closer to the spirit of the peasant kitchen than preening cooks with all their blather about "only tomato, basil, mozzarella, and anchovies fished on a Thursday".</p><blockquote><p>I also hardly ever put cheese on top. Last time I used mozzerella it oozed liquid all over the place and made the base soggy.</p></blockquote><p>This used to be a problem I had. Cut it into slices beforehand, and gently squeeze out as much moisture as you can. It will retain plenty to be nice when melted, but not so much that it coughs up liquid all over your pizza.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
				<li class="comment-tools">
					<ul>
						<li class="recomended">
							
